---
description: Security, compliance, and PII rules for the entire repository
alwaysApply: true
---

Security rules:
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, tokens, credentials, or private URLs (Twilio, OpenAI, PostgreSQL, Redis, etc.).
- Never log passwords, tokens, raw secrets, or sensitive user content.
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs (forms, API requests, webhooks).
- Treat uploads, URLs, prompts, and external content as untrusted.
- Enforce authentication and authorization on protected resources; use RBAC (Super Admin, Tenant Admin, Manager, Agent).
- Use least-privilege access patterns; add rate limiting to sensitive or expensive endpoints.
- Use secure defaults.

Multi-tenant isolation:
- Every database query on tenant-scoped data MUST filter by tenant_id.
- Agents must only access leads, calls, and data within their own tenant.
- API endpoints must enforce tenant scoping at the dependency/middleware level.
- Never expose one tenant's data to another tenant.

Call recording and PII:
- Call recordings contain sensitive PII; store encrypted and access-controlled.
- Implement data retention policies for recordings (configurable per tenant).
- Mask or redact PII in logs and analytics where required.
- Maintain audit logs for sensitive actions (call recording access, lead export, admin changes).

AI-specific security:
- Validate and sanitize inputs before sending to OpenAI APIs.
- Handle unsafe model output before returning to the user.
- Do not expose system prompts or internal AI configuration to end users.
- Rate limit AI-heavy endpoints to prevent abuse and cost overruns.

Do not:
- Assume client-side validation is enough.
- Return internal exception details to users.
- Trust LLM output without validation in critical paths.
- Store unencrypted secrets in environment files committed to git.
